{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti Chapter 8 (also known as the *Manusmṛti* or *Laws of Manu*), the rules on lending money at interest appear primarily in verses 140–154**, as part of the broader discussion on debts (the first of the eighteen titles of law; see 8.4). These specify permissible interest rates, limits, types of interest, pledges, and related prohibitions.[^1][^2]\n\nKey provisions include:\n- A moneylender may charge interest at 1.25% per month (the \"eightieth part\" of the principal), per the prescription of Vasishtha; alternatively, 2% monthly is allowable without sin.[^3]\n- Rates vary by *varṇa*: 2% for Brāhmaṇas, 3% for Kṣatriyas, 4% for Vaiśyas, and 5% for Śūdras.[^4]\n- Interest cannot be charged on usable pledges; pledges cannot be forfeited by time lapse or sold, and unauthorized use forfeits interest.[^5]\n- Total interest is capped (e.g., double the principal generally; fivefold for grain, etc.); compound, periodic, stipulated, or labor-based interest is forbidden.[^6]\n\nThese rules emphasize ethical limits to prevent usury while allowing capital growth, integrated into judicial procedures for debt recovery (8.47–60). For the full context, read verses 8.1–420 on judicial matters.[^7]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 8, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-85e12e).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 8, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-85e12e).\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 8, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-85e12e).\n[^4]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 8, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-b774d8).\n[^5]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 8, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-73fef8).\n[^6]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 8, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-dc4c89).\n[^7]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 8, [full chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/).",
